## 7. Permission Flow, Policy, Seeder, and Frontend Response

Permission handling must be easy to read from backend code, safe for authorization, and easy for the frontend to render as grouped checkboxes, tabs, cards, or menus.

The permission system must support both permission depths:

```text
{group}.{action}                  // 2 layers
{module}.{section}.{action}        // 3 layers
```

Examples:

```text
users.view                         // 2 layers
roles.update                       // 2 layers
products.ai.menu                   // 3 layers
products.ai.view                   // 3 layers
products.categories.create         // 3 layers
```

The important rule is:

```text
PermissionGroup value + PermissionAction value = final permission name
```

So:

```php
PermissionGroup::PRODUCT_AI->value      // products.ai
PermissionAction::MENU->value           // menu

PermissionNameResolver::resolve(
    PermissionGroup::PRODUCT_AI,
    PermissionAction::MENU,
);                                      // products.ai.menu
```

Do not create separate code paths for 2-layer and 3-layer permissions. The group key may contain one segment, like `users`, or two segments, like `products.ai`. The resolver appends the action in both cases.

The flow is:

```text
PermissionModule enum
        ↓
PermissionAction enum
        ↓
PermissionGroup enum defines group key, module, labels, section, actions
        ↓
PermissionNameResolver builds users.view or products.ai.menu
        ↓
PermissionCatalog builds all permissions once from enums
        ↓
Seeder bulk-upserts permissions into DB
        ↓
Policy checks permission through AuthorizesByPermissionGroup
        ↓
Controller calls policy using `$this->authorize(...)`
        ↓
API returns grouped permissions with frontend labels and allowed map
```

---

### 7.1 Permission naming convention

Use these naming rules:

| Type | Format | Example |
|---|---|---|
| 2 layers | `{group}.{action}` | `users.view` |
| 3 layers | `{module}.{section}.{action}` | `products.ai.menu` |

Rules:

- Permission names must be generated only by `PermissionNameResolver`.
- Do not hardcode permission strings in controllers, policies, seeders, tests, or frontend response builders.
- Keep `PermissionGroup` as the resource or feature path.
- Keep `PermissionAction` as the final action.
- A `PermissionGroup` value may contain one or two segments only.
- Final permission names should contain two or three segments only.
- Avoid permission names deeper than three segments unless the project has a confirmed need.

Good:

```text
users.view
products.ai.menu
products.categories.update
orders.refunds.approve
```

Avoid:

```text
products.ai.menu.open.sidebar
products.ai.menu.button.click
```

If the project later needs a different separator or naming format, update `PermissionNameResolver` only.

---

### 7.2 PermissionModule enum

Use a module enum so the frontend can group permissions consistently without repeating raw strings.

**Where**: `App\Enums\PermissionModule`

```php
<?php

declare(strict_types=1);

namespace App\Enums;

enum PermissionModule: string
{
    case CORE = 'core';
    case PRODUCTS = 'products';
    case CLEANING = 'cleaning';
    case RESTURANTS = 'resturants';
    case SUPERMARKET = 'supermarket';

    public function label(): string
    {
        return match ($this) {
            self::CORE => 'Core',
            self::PRODUCTS => 'Products',
            self::CLEANING => 'Cleaning',
            self::RESTURANTS => 'Resturants',
            self::SUPERMARKET => 'Supermarket',
        };
    }

    public function order(): int
    {
        return match ($this) {
            self::CORE => 10,
            self::PRODUCTS => 20,
            self::CLEANING => 100,
            self::RESTURANTS => 200,
            self::SUPERMARKET => 300,
        };
    }
}
```

Use `PermissionModule` only for metadata and frontend grouping. It is not directly used to authorize actions.

---

### 7.3 PermissionAction enum

Use one enum for reusable actions. Add non-CRUD actions here only when they are actually used by at least one permission group.

**Where**: `App\Enums\PermissionAction`

```php
<?php

declare(strict_types=1);

namespace App\Enums;

enum PermissionAction: string
{
    case VIEW = 'view';
    case CREATE = 'create';
    case UPDATE = 'update';
    case DELETE = 'delete';

    case MENU = 'menu';
    case RUN = 'run';
    case IMPORT = 'import';
    case EXPORT = 'export';
    case APPROVE = 'approve';
    case REJECT = 'reject';

    public function label(): string
    {
        return match ($this) {
            self::VIEW => 'View',
            self::CREATE => 'Create',
            self::UPDATE => 'Update',
            self::DELETE => 'Delete',
            self::MENU => 'Show Menu',
            self::RUN => 'Run',
            self::IMPORT => 'Import',
            self::EXPORT => 'Export',
            self::APPROVE => 'Approve',
            self::REJECT => 'Reject',
        };
    }

    /**
     * @return list<self>
     */
    public static function crud(): array
    {
        return [
            self::VIEW,
            self::CREATE,
            self::UPDATE,
            self::DELETE,
        ];
    }

    /**
     * @return list<self>
     */
    public static function readOnly(): array
    {
        return [self::VIEW];
    }
}
```

Rules:

- Do not duplicate actions per resource.
- Do not write actions as raw strings like `'menu'` or `'approve'` outside this enum.
- If a new action is required, add it once here, then reuse it from any group.

---

### 7.4 Permission group definition object

Use a small definition object to avoid repeating metadata methods and to keep `PermissionGroup` readable.

**Where**: `App\Support\Permissions\PermissionGroupDefinition`

```php
<?php

declare(strict_types=1);

namespace App\Support\Permissions;

use App\Enums\PermissionAction;
use App\Enums\PermissionModule;

final readonly class PermissionGroupDefinition
{
    /**
     * @param list<PermissionAction>|null $actions
     */
    public function __construct(
        public string $label,
        public PermissionModule $module,
        public string $description,
        public int $order,
        public ?string $sectionLabel = null,
        public ?array $actions = null,
    ) {}
}
```

Why this pattern is used:

- `PermissionGroup` stays as the single catalog source.
- Labels, module grouping, section labels, description, order, and actions are defined once.
- Adding a new permission group does not require changing the seeder, catalog service, response service, or resolver.

---

### 7.5 PermissionGroup enum with 2-layer and 3-layer support

`PermissionGroup` is the catalog of protected resources/features.

**Where**: `App\Enums\PermissionGroup`

```php
<?php

declare(strict_types=1);

namespace App\Enums;

use App\Support\Permissions\PermissionGroupDefinition;

enum PermissionGroup: string
{
    // 2-layer permissions: users.view, roles.create
    case USER = 'users';
    case ROLE = 'roles';

    // 3-layer permissions: products.ai.menu, products.categories.view
    case PRODUCT_AI = 'products.ai';
    case PRODUCT_CATEGORY = 'products.categories';
    case PRODUCT_IMPORT = 'products.import';

    // Module examples
    case CLEANING_BOOKING = 'cleaning-bookings';
    case RESTURANT_ORDER = 'resturant-orders';
    case SUPERMARKET_PRODUCT = 'supermarket-products';

    public function definition(): PermissionGroupDefinition
    {
        return match ($this) {
            self::USER => new PermissionGroupDefinition(
                label: 'Users',
                module: PermissionModule::CORE,
                description: 'Manage application users.',
                order: 10,
            ),

            self::ROLE => new PermissionGroupDefinition(
                label: 'Roles',
                module: PermissionModule::CORE,
                description: 'Manage roles and assigned permissions.',
                order: 20,
            ),

            self::PRODUCT_AI => new PermissionGroupDefinition(
                label: 'Product AI',
                module: PermissionModule::PRODUCTS,
                description: 'Control product AI tools and menu visibility.',
                order: 110,
                sectionLabel: 'AI',
                actions: [
                    PermissionAction::MENU,
                    PermissionAction::VIEW,
                    PermissionAction::RUN,
                    PermissionAction::UPDATE,
                ],
            ),

            self::PRODUCT_CATEGORY => new PermissionGroupDefinition(
                label: 'Product Categories',
                module: PermissionModule::PRODUCTS,
                description: 'Manage product categories.',
                order: 120,
                sectionLabel: 'Categories',
            ),

            self::PRODUCT_IMPORT => new PermissionGroupDefinition(
                label: 'Product Import',
                module: PermissionModule::PRODUCTS,
                description: 'Import and review product catalog data.',
                order: 130,
                sectionLabel: 'Import',
                actions: [
                    PermissionAction::VIEW,
                    PermissionAction::IMPORT,
                    PermissionAction::EXPORT,
                ],
            ),

            self::CLEANING_BOOKING => new PermissionGroupDefinition(
                label: 'Cleaning Bookings',
                module: PermissionModule::CLEANING,
                description: 'Manage cleaning service bookings.',
                order: 210,
            ),

            self::RESTURANT_ORDER => new PermissionGroupDefinition(
                label: 'Resturant Orders',
                module: PermissionModule::RESTURANTS,
                description: 'Manage resturant orders.',
                order: 310,
            ),

            self::SUPERMARKET_PRODUCT => new PermissionGroupDefinition(
                label: 'Supermarket Products',
                module: PermissionModule::SUPERMARKET,
                description: 'Manage supermarket products.',
                order: 410,
            ),
        };
    }

    public function label(): string
    {
        return $this->definition()->label;
    }

    public function module(): PermissionModule
    {
        return $this->definition()->module;
    }

    public function moduleKey(): string
    {
        return $this->module()->value;
    }

    public function moduleLabel(): string
    {
        return $this->module()->label();
    }

    public function sectionKey(): ?string
    {
        $segments = explode('.', $this->value);

        return count($segments) === 2 ? $segments[1] : null;
    }

    public function sectionLabel(): ?string
    {
        return $this->definition()->sectionLabel;
    }

    public function description(): string
    {
        return $this->definition()->description;
    }

    public function order(): int
    {
        return $this->definition()->order;
    }

    /**
     * @return list<PermissionAction>
     */
    public function actions(): array
    {
        return $this->definition()->actions ?? PermissionAction::crud();
    }

    public function depth(): int
    {
        return substr_count($this->value, '.') + 1;
    }
}
```

Rules:

- For 2-layer permissions, use a one-segment group value: `users`, `roles`.
- For 3-layer permissions, use a two-segment group value: `products.ai`, `products.categories`.
- Never include the action inside `PermissionGroup` value.
- The action is always appended by `PermissionNameResolver`.
- `sectionLabel` is used only for 3-layer groups.
- `actions` is optional. If omitted, the group uses full CRUD.

Adding a new permission group should usually require only one new enum case and one new `definition()` entry.

Example:

```php
case PRODUCT_REVIEWS = 'products.reviews';
```

```php
self::PRODUCT_REVIEWS => new PermissionGroupDefinition(
    label: 'Product Reviews',
    module: PermissionModule::PRODUCTS,
    description: 'Moderate product reviews.',
    order: 140,
    sectionLabel: 'Reviews',
    actions: [
        PermissionAction::VIEW,
        PermissionAction::APPROVE,
        PermissionAction::REJECT,
        PermissionAction::DELETE,
    ],
),
```

No seeder, API response builder, or policy helper needs to change.

