### 7.8 Permission policy flow

Policies must be explicit about which permission group they protect.

**Where**: `App\Policies\{Model}Policy`

The policy should:

- Use `AuthorizesByPermissionGroup`.
- Define `permissionGroup()` to make the mapping obvious.
- Map Laravel policy abilities to `PermissionAction`.
- Avoid raw permission strings.

**Trait example:**

```php
<?php

declare(strict_types=1);

namespace App\Policies\Concerns;

use App\Enums\PermissionAction;
use App\Enums\PermissionGroup;
use App\Models\User;
use App\Support\Permissions\PermissionNameResolver;

trait AuthorizesByPermissionGroup
{
    abstract protected function permissionGroup(): PermissionGroup;

    protected function authorizeAction(User $user, PermissionAction $action): bool
    {
        return $user->can(
            PermissionNameResolver::resolve($this->permissionGroup(), $action)
        );
    }
}
```

**2-layer policy example:**

```php
<?php

declare(strict_types=1);

namespace App\Policies;

use App\Enums\PermissionAction;
use App\Enums\PermissionGroup;
use App\Models\User;
use App\Policies\Concerns\AuthorizesByPermissionGroup;

class UserPolicy
{
    use AuthorizesByPermissionGroup;

    protected function permissionGroup(): PermissionGroup
    {
        return PermissionGroup::USER;
    }

    public function viewAny(User $user): bool
    {
        return $this->authorizeAction($user, PermissionAction::VIEW);
    }

    public function view(User $user, User $model): bool
    {
        return $this->authorizeAction($user, PermissionAction::VIEW);
    }

    public function create(User $user): bool
    {
        return $this->authorizeAction($user, PermissionAction::CREATE);
    }

    public function update(User $user, User $model): bool
    {
        return $this->authorizeAction($user, PermissionAction::UPDATE);
    }

    public function delete(User $user, User $model): bool
    {
        return $this->authorizeAction($user, PermissionAction::DELETE);
    }
}
```

**3-layer policy example:**

```php
class ProductAiPolicy
{
    use AuthorizesByPermissionGroup;

    protected function permissionGroup(): PermissionGroup
    {
        return PermissionGroup::PRODUCT_AI;
    }

    public function viewAny(User $user): bool
    {
        return $this->authorizeAction($user, PermissionAction::VIEW);
    }

    public function showMenu(User $user): bool
    {
        return $this->authorizeAction($user, PermissionAction::MENU);
    }

    public function run(User $user): bool
    {
        return $this->authorizeAction($user, PermissionAction::RUN);
    }

    public function update(User $user): bool
    {
        return $this->authorizeAction($user, PermissionAction::UPDATE);
    }
}
```

This resolves to:

```text
products.ai.view
products.ai.menu
products.ai.run
products.ai.update
```

---

### 7.9 Controller authorization flow

Controllers must call policy methods clearly.

Do not rely on hidden authorization behavior unless the project already uses it consistently.

**Recommended explicit CRUD flow:**

```php
public function index(UserFilterRequest $request): AnonymousResourceCollection
{
    $this->authorize('viewAny', User::class);

    $users = User::getQuery()
        ->paginate($request->get('perPage', 20));

    return UserResource::collection($users);
}

public function store(StoreUserRequest $request): UserResource
{
    $this->authorize('create', User::class);

    $user = $this->userService->store(UserData::from($request->validated()));

    return UserResource::make($user);
}

public function show(User $user): UserResource
{
    $this->authorize('view', $user);

    return UserResource::make($user);
}

public function update(UpdateUserRequest $request, User $user): UserResource
{
    $this->authorize('update', $user);

    $user = $this->userService->update(UserData::from($request->validated()), $user);

    return UserResource::make($user);
}

public function destroy(User $user): Response
{
    $this->authorize('delete', $user);

    $user->delete();

    return response()->noContent();
}
```

Mapping:

| Controller Method | Policy Ability | Permission Action |
|---|---|---|
| `index` | `viewAny` | `view` |
| `show` | `view` | `view` |
| `store` | `create` | `create` |
| `update` | `update` | `update` |
| `destroy` | `delete` | `delete` |

**Custom action example:**

```php
public function menu(Request $request): JsonResponse
{
    $this->authorize('showMenu', ProductAi::class);

    return response()->json([
        'data' => $this->productAiService->menu(),
    ]);
}

public function run(RunProductAiRequest $request): JsonResponse
{
    $this->authorize('run', ProductAi::class);

    return response()->json([
        'data' => $this->productAiService->run($request->validated()),
    ]);
}
```

