### 7.14 Testing permission flow

Every CRUD feature must test authorization.

Minimum tests:

- User without permission receives `403`.
- User with `group.view` can access `index` and `show`.
- User with `group.create` can access `store`.
- User with `group.update` can access `update`.
- User with `group.delete` can access `destroy`.
- User with a 3-layer permission like `products.ai.menu` can access the custom action.
- `/me/permissions` returns modules, groups, labels, flat map, and granted list.

Example:

```php
it('allows user with users view permission to list users', function () {
    $user = User::factory()->create();

    $user->givePermissionTo(
        PermissionNameResolver::resolve(PermissionGroup::USER, PermissionAction::VIEW)
    );

    actingAs($user)
        ->getJson('/api/users')
        ->assertOk();
});

it('allows user with product ai menu permission to view ai menu', function () {
    $user = User::factory()->create();

    $user->givePermissionTo(
        PermissionNameResolver::resolve(PermissionGroup::PRODUCT_AI, PermissionAction::MENU)
    );

    actingAs($user)
        ->getJson('/api/products/ai/menu')
        ->assertOk();
});

it('returns grouped permissions for frontend', function () {
    $user = User::factory()->create();

    $user->givePermissionTo(
        PermissionNameResolver::resolve(PermissionGroup::USER, PermissionAction::VIEW)
    );

    $response = actingAs($user)
        ->getJson('/api/me/permissions')
        ->assertOk()
        ->assertJsonPath('data.modules.0.key', 'core');

    $flat = $response->json('data.flat');

    expect($flat['users.view'])->toBeTrue();
});
```

Important test note:

Because flat permission names contain dots, avoid `assertJsonPath('data.flat.users.view', true)`. That path may be interpreted as nested JSON. Read `data.flat` first, then assert using the full permission name as the array key.

---

### 7.15 Performance and maintainability rules

Follow these rules to keep permission code fast and easy to extend:

- Use `PermissionNameResolver` for all permission names.
- Use `PermissionCatalog` for all generated permission lists.
- Do not repeat nested `PermissionGroup::cases()` loops across seeders, controllers, and services.
- Use `upsert` in seeders instead of `firstOrCreate` per permission.
- Clear Spatie permission cache before and after seeding.
- Do not call `$user->can()` repeatedly while building the frontend permission catalog.
- Use `$user->getAllPermissions()->pluck('name')->flip()` once for API response building.
- Keep permission metadata backend-owned. Frontend should consume labels, modules, and sections from the API.
- Do not store labels or descriptions in role payloads.
- Do not create permissions dynamically from frontend input.
- For custom permissions, add a new `PermissionAction` once, then reuse it.
- For new resources/features, add a `PermissionGroup` case and definition only.

---

### 7.16 Permission implementation checklist

For a normal CRUD permission:

- [ ] Add a `PermissionGroup` enum case.
- [ ] Add one `definition()` entry with label, module, description, and order.
- [ ] Keep `actions` empty if the group uses full CRUD.
- [ ] Run the permissions seeder.
- [ ] Add the policy with explicit `permissionGroup()`.
- [ ] Use `PermissionAction` enum in the policy.
- [ ] Add `$this->authorize(...)` in every controller method.
- [ ] Add Pest tests for denied and allowed access.

For a 3-layer or custom permission:

- [ ] Add or reuse the needed `PermissionAction`, such as `MENU`, `RUN`, or `APPROVE`.
- [ ] Add a `PermissionGroup` enum case with a two-segment value, such as `products.ai`.
- [ ] Add `sectionLabel` for frontend grouping.
- [ ] Define custom `actions` if the group does not use full CRUD.
- [ ] Add custom policy methods, such as `showMenu()` or `run()`.
- [ ] Add controller authorization for those custom policy methods.
- [ ] Confirm `/me/permissions` returns the permission in `modules`, `flat`, and `granted` when allowed.
- [ ] Add tests for the custom action.

